doc_id=118 page=3 block_id=3-9 bbox=72.0,266.48,538.95,399.43 label=bbtb 104 113
line=104 fonts=F0-10.9 bbox=88.92,388.52,538.95,399.43           :    The common   denominator  of all these different types of meanings is the bounded or telic event that the
line=105 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.25 bbox=72.0,374.96,538.88,385.87:construction seems to describe. Indeed, it has been claimed that this class of light verbs is really a class of
line=106 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.25 bbox=72.0,361.4,538.89,372.31 :aspectual auxiliaries giving rise to perfectives in the language (e.g., Hook 1991, Hook 1993). However, as
line=107 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.17 bbox=72.0,347.84,538.4,358.75 :we  show in the next section, the light verbs in question do not pattern with auxiliaries either syntactically
line=108 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.28 bbox=72.0,334.28,538.69,345.19:or morphologically.  While  it is true that the light verb seems to create accomplishment or achievement
line=109 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.17 bbox=72.0,320.72,538.85,331.63:predicates, this is crucially different from the role of an actual perfective tense form or auxiliary (see Butt
line=110 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.22 bbox=72.0,307.16,538.89,318.07:and Geuder  2001  for detailed argumentation, also Bashir 1993 for similar conclusions). In particular, the
line=111 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.07 bbox=72.0,293.6,538.84,304.51 :resulting accomplishments/achievements  are not necessarily perfective in broader (outer) aspectual terms,
line=112 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.11 bbox=72.0,280.04,538.6,290.95 :but occur in all the tense/aspect forms of the language see (6b) for an example  of the accomplishment
line=113 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.17 bbox=72.0,266.48,441.74,277.39:predicate derived via this kind of construction occuring in the past continuous tense).

