doc_id=118 page=4 block_id=4-2 bbox=72.0,367.88,539.06,717.55 label=tb 125 150
line=125 fonts=F0-10.9,F5-10.9 bbox=88.92,706.64,538.55,717.55    :    Significantly, the effect of this construction is to create a different kind of aktionsart, a distinction
line=126 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.22 bbox=72.0,693.08,538.73,703.99 :traditionally taken to be encoded within lexical items. This is a further factor in the impression that complex
line=127 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.39 bbox=72.0,679.52,450.51,690.43 :predicates of the ‘result’ type are more tightly bound as a unit than the other two types.
line=128 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.00 bbox=88.92,665.96,538.83,676.87:    In each of these cases, two separate lexical items combine compositionally to produce a more complex
line=129 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.28 bbox=72.0,652.4,538.77,663.31  :type of predication. This is not unusual in itself—there are many cases in natural language where a clausal
line=130 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.22 bbox=72.0,638.84,538.64,649.75 :or infinitival projection forms the complement to a higher matrix verb. The fact that this language exhibits
line=131 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.24 bbox=72.0,625.28,539.04,636.19 :a word  order pattern which can be described as ‘head-final’ means that a subordinating construction will
line=132 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.39 bbox=72.0,611.72,538.75,622.63 :result in a sentence where the matrix verb and the subordinated non-finite verb are linearly adjacent. In such
line=133 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.22 bbox=72.0,598.16,539.06,609.07 :a case we would  be dealing with a simple biclausal construction with a nonfinite subordinate clause. At
line=134 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.10 bbox=72.0,584.6,538.95,595.51  :the other end of the spectrum, it is possible, and commonplace, for a main verb to occur with one or more
line=135 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.29 bbox=72.0,571.16,538.75,582.07 :‘auxiliaries’ which simply modify the eventuality description in particular ways and which carry the tense
line=136 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.06 bbox=72.0,557.6,538.93,568.51  :and agreement  inflection of the clause. Here the construction would be monoclausal, but once again, the
line=137 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.11 bbox=72.0,544.04,538.65,554.95 :‘head-final’ language would express this with a word order in which the main verb and auxiliary are linearly
line=138 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.33 bbox=72.0,530.48,538.8,541.39  :adjacent. Our  three types of construction delineated above could in principle belong to either of these
line=139 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.12 bbox=72.0,516.92,538.38,527.83 :two combinatoric  possibilities, neither of which would be particularly interesting from a crosslinguistic
line=140 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.16 bbox=72.0,503.36,538.88,514.27 :perspective. In the first section of the paper, we labor to convince the reader that the complex predicates of
line=141 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.26 bbox=72.0,489.8,538.84,500.71  :the ‘let’ and ‘result’ types do not fall neatly into either the monoclausal or biclausal characterization given
line=142 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.18 bbox=72.0,476.24,538.86,487.15 :above, but represent a decomposition of verbal meaning that is traditionally carried by single lexical items
line=143 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.06 bbox=72.0,462.68,295.56,473.59 :in languages of the more familiar European variety.
line=144 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.00 bbox=88.92,449.12,538.94,460.03:    In section 3, we compare complex  predicates to auxiliary constructions, and argue that the light verb
line=145 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.19 bbox=72.0,435.56,538.67,446.47 :is not an auxiliary and carries more information than the kind of functional and grammatical information
line=146 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.19 bbox=72.0,422.12,538.83,433.03 :traditionally associated with auxiliaries. In section 4, we demonstrate that the ‘tell’ type contrasts with the
line=147 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.29 bbox=72.0,408.56,538.9,419.47  :‘let’ type and the ‘result’ type in that only the former can be shown to be a biclausal construction from the
line=148 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.10 bbox=72.0,395.0,538.91,405.91  :point of view of all the diagnostics available to us in the language. The section ends with a summary of the
line=149 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.10 bbox=72.0,381.44,538.87,392.35 :paradoxial properties of the ‘let’ and ‘result’ complex predicates which will be the focus of the analysis in
line=150 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.11 bbox=72.0,367.88,160.59,378.79 :subsequent sections.

