line=151 fonts=F1-14.3 bbox=72.0,332.72,282.1,347.07:3  Light Verbs are not Auxiliaries

doc_id=118 page=4 block_id=4-4 bbox=72.0,226.64,538.89,318.79 label=bbt 152 158
line=152 fonts=F0-10.9 bbox=72.0,307.88,538.76,318.79                   :Light verbs in Hindi/Urdu appear to make a functional contribution to the sentence as they signal the incep-
line=153 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.11 bbox=72.0,294.32,538.65,305.23       :tion or completion of an event (among other things). For these reasons, light verbs have often been classed
line=154 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.17 bbox=72.0,280.76,538.89,291.67       :as a type of auxiliary. However, there is good evidence that Hindi/Urdu does possess auxiliaries, and that
line=155 fonts=F0-10.9,F4-8.0 iscore=0.18 bbox=72.0,267.32,453.83,279.25:light verbs are syntactically and distributionally distinct from them in number of ways.^{7}
line=156 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.18 bbox=88.92,253.76,538.7,264.67       :    First it should be noted that the ordering within the Hindi/Urdu verbal complex is strict and requires
line=157 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.12 bbox=72.0,240.2,538.66,251.11        :a distinction to be made between main  verbs, light verbs, the passive (formed with ‘go’), the progressive
line=158 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.12 bbox=72.0,226.64,208.48,237.55       :auxiliary and the ‘be’ auxiliary.

