doc_id=118 page=10 block_id=10-9 bbox=72.0,223.4,538.87,342.67 label=bbbttb 382 390
line=382 fonts=F0-10.9 bbox=72.0,331.76,538.86,342.67            :The central problem that this paper seeks to address, then, is the representation of complex predicates of the
line=383 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.17 bbox=72.0,318.2,538.66,329.11 :‘result’ type and the ‘let’ type above. These two constructions can be shown to be neither simple auxiliary
line=384 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.22 bbox=72.0,304.64,538.86,315.55:constructions nor biclausal complementation structures. Rather, both parts of the verbal complex seem to be
line=385 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.47 bbox=72.0,291.2,538.48,302.11 :implicated in the argument structure and case-marking possibilities of the construction, and both contribute
line=386 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.24 bbox=72.0,277.64,538.87,288.55:to the overall aktionsart of the event. Given these facts, and given the close integrity of the two parts of the
line=387 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.19 bbox=72.0,264.08,538.85,274.99:complex  verb, it is tempting to classify them as purely ‘lexical’ constructions with no syntactic autonomy for
line=388 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.22 bbox=72.0,250.52,538.84,261.43:the individual pieces. However, this view is clearly not correct. For both types of construction, the light verb
line=389 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.22 bbox=72.0,236.96,538.42,247.87:may  move  away  from the main verb under certain discourse conditions, in particular under topicalization,
line=390 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.20 bbox=72.0,223.4,370.91,234.31 :as shown in examples (26) and (27) (see Butt 1995 for more details).

