line=418 fonts=F0-10.9 bbox=75.6,436.52,300.14,447.43              : (28) Miriam  drank 5 whiskies in the pub last night.
line=419 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.25 bbox=105.36,422.96,445.52,433.87:       e[drinking(e; ‘Miriam’,‘5whiskies’) & last-night(e) & in-the-pub(e) & Cul(e)]

doc_id=118 page=11 block_id=11-6 bbox=72.0,185.6,539.86,410.11 label=bbbtb 420 434
line=420 fonts=F0-10.9 bbox=88.92,399.2,538.79,410.11                   :    Our approach will share the intuition of the neo-Davidsonian position that event variables are a crucial
line=421 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.05 bbox=72.0,385.64,538.84,396.55       :element in the logical representation of sentences. We will take this a little further, and assume that the event
line=422 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.32 bbox=72.0,372.08,538.86,382.99       :position classically taken to be associated with a single lexical item may actually be internally complex. In
line=423 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.18 bbox=72.0,358.52,538.52,369.43       :other words, we believe that certain complex events can be decomposed into subevents which are potentially
line=424 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.11 bbox=72.0,344.96,538.99,355.87       :events in their own right, but which can combine  in a number of systematic ways  to produce the more
line=425 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.21 bbox=72.0,331.4,538.9,342.31         :complex  forms. The possibilities for event combination at this level are not simply mereological as in the
line=426 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.29 bbox=72.0,317.84,538.86,328.75       :lattice-theoretic approach of Link 1983, but correspond to two distinct types of event-event relation which
