line=495 fonts=F0-10.9 bbox=88.92,361.04,538.79,371.95            :    For concreteness, we show here how we envisage the semantic interpretation of this structure being built
line=496 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.22 bbox=72.0,347.48,538.92,358.39 :up. Here  we take particular nodes in the first phase syntax tree to denote relations between properties of
line=497 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.06 bbox=72.0,333.92,538.91,344.83 :events and properties of events, constructing more and more complex event descriptions. Under this more
line=498 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.12 bbox=72.0,320.36,538.83,331.27 :‘constructionist’ view, neither events nor individual entities are arguments of the lexical item itself, but of
line=499 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.25 bbox=72.0,306.92,538.86,317.83 :the predicates introduced by the semantic interpretation of particular categorial nodes; however, like the
line=500 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.13 bbox=72.0,293.36,538.86,304.27 :neo-Davidsonian  position, events and individuals are never all co-arguments of the same predicate, and they
line=501 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.20 bbox=72.0,279.8,213.76,290.71  :are discharged in different ways.
line=502 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.12 bbox=88.92,266.24,538.94,277.15:    In what follows we lay out a kind of ‘Post-Davidsonian’ semantics which interprets the verbal heads of
line=503 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.22 bbox=72.0,252.68,538.64,263.59 :the l-syntax in a regular and systematic way. As discussed above, there are two primitive modes of sub-event
line=504 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.11 bbox=72.0,239.12,238.68,250.03 :composition to create complex events:

