line=613 fonts=F0-10.9 bbox=88.92,505.88,538.63,516.79                   :    We believe it is no accident that causative semantics is associated with this type of light verb that displays
line=614 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.26 bbox=72.0,492.32,538.87,503.23        :the paradoxical properties we have outlined. If the light verb were actually part of the first phase syntax (or
line=615 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.32 bbox=72.0,478.88,538.79,489.79        :‘lexical syntax’ in the Hale and Keyser sense) it would contribute the kind of meaning most commonly found
line=616 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.26 bbox=72.0,465.32,538.73,476.23        :within lexical items. It would show great integrity with the other portions of the first phase syntax, and affect
line=617 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.11 bbox=72.0,451.76,538.68,462.67        :the case marking  and argument  structure of a single ‘monoclause’. Since it is part of the event structure
line=618 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.17 bbox=72.0,438.2,538.51,449.11         :decomposition  of the e bound by tense, it will not show the properties of modifying auxiliaries or contribute
line=619 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.16 bbox=72.0,424.64,538.71,435.55        :to ‘external aspect’ (in the Verkuyl 1972 sense); rather, it will contribute to the aktionsart of the basic verbal
line=620 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.32 bbox=72.0,411.08,538.9,421.99         :event. We  predict further that such an element would be distributionally and behaviourally distinct from
line=621 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.25 bbox=72.0,397.52,538.61,408.43        :heads that are external to the vP phase (auxiliaries). In addition, given the head-final typological character
line=622 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.18 bbox=72.0,383.96,538.81,394.87        :of this language, we find that the structure of the first phase syntax (proposed for independent semantic
line=623 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.06 bbox=72.0,370.4,538.85,381.31         :and linguistic reasons) predicts that a lexically instantiated little v head bearing causative semantics and
line=624 fonts=F0-10.9,F5-10.9 iscore=0.12 bbox=72.0,356.84,536.85,367.75:determining the properties of the external argument, would follow a main verb that instantiated the V head.
line=625 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.25 bbox=88.92,343.28,538.93,354.19       :    For these reasons, we assume  that constructions of the ‘let’ type are complex lexical structures where
line=626 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.30 bbox=72.0,329.84,538.92,340.75        :the light verb (V2) is an overt instantiation of little v (see Diesing 1998 for a related proposal in which
line=627 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.15 bbox=72.0,316.28,538.89,327.19        :light verbs are situated in a special projection), and V1 is the main verbal predicate. Thus, the macro event
line=628 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.21 bbox=72.0,302.72,539.24,313.63        :‘write-let’ actually represents two subevents, that of instigating an action (e , the cause), which introduces
line=629 fonts=F0-10.9,F4-8.0 iscore=0.12 bbox=72.0,289.16,349.07,301.09 :an agent and implies the caused event e , namely, the writing.^{15}
line=630 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.06 bbox=88.92,275.6,538.93,286.51        :    In the representations that follow, we augment the argument structures of the individual pieces of the
line=631 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.19 bbox=72.0,262.04,538.7,272.95         :complex  event to indicate the arguments that are associated with each subevent.  We  assume  (following
line=632 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.17 bbox=72.0,248.48,538.94,259.39        :Ramchand   2002)  that the verbs of the ‘write’ type do not obligatorily encode an RP (result phrase); the
line=633 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.22 bbox=72.0,234.92,538.77,245.83        :two arguments  associated with ‘write’ are the specifier of the writing process (the entity doing the action)
line=634 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.26 bbox=72.0,221.36,538.81,232.27        :and the complement  DP  to that process head which describes the path of the writing event (the thing being
line=635 fonts=F0-10.9,F4-8.0 iscore=0.05 bbox=72.0,207.8,116.98,219.73  :written).^{16}
