line=909 fonts=F0-10.9 bbox=72.0,589.88,538.87,600.79                     :In this paper, we have argued that there are three distinct types of V1-V2 constructions in Hindi/Urdu. Using
line=910 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.16 bbox=72.0,576.32,538.87,587.23         :the syntactic diagnostics made available by the language, we argued that one type, the ‘tell’ type, was a case
line=911 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.32 bbox=72.0,562.76,538.83,573.67         :of genuine syntactic and semantic subordination. The other two types are what we  would call ‘complex
line=912 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.26 bbox=72.0,549.2,538.92,560.11          :predicates’ in the sense that V1 and V2 combine to form a single complete functional complex. In the ‘let’
line=913 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.11 bbox=72.0,535.64,538.66,546.55         :type, we argued that V1 and V2 were  lexical instantiations of V and v in the lexical structure respectively.
line=914 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.20 bbox=72.0,522.08,538.83,532.99         :In the ‘result’ type, we found that V1 and V2 instantiate R and V/(v) respectively, where R was the head
line=915 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.40 bbox=72.0,508.52,538.89,519.43         :of the projection representing the final state achieved by the direct object. We were able to account for the
line=916 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.11 bbox=72.0,494.96,538.88,505.87         :(sometimes  surprising) aspectual readings within these complex predicates precisely because our view of
line=917 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.11 bbox=72.0,481.4,538.65,492.31          :event building allows us to posit a more complex interaction between parts of the syntax and the semantics.
line=918 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.24 bbox=88.92,467.84,538.94,478.75        :    If our analysis is correct, complex constructions in Hindi/Urdu are a test case which therefore offer
line=919 fonts=F0-10.9,F12-23.3 iscore=0.06 bbox=72.0,440.84,538.96,465.19:strikingform proposedsyntactichere, semantic‘causationandOQPmorphologicalprocess, resultevidenceR ’ whichin favorcanofbeanseeneventtostructureunderlie decompositionverbal predicationof thein
line=920 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.10 bbox=72.0,427.28,146.59,438.19         :natural language.
line=921 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.00 bbox=88.92,413.72,538.94,424.63        :    The ‘first phase’ syntax proposed here makes use of three basic components, or subevents, that are cen-
line=922 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.11 bbox=72.0,400.16,538.79,411.07         :tral to the analysis of these phenomena: the causing subevent vP; the process subevent, VP; and the result
line=923 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.11 bbox=72.0,386.6,538.68,397.51          :state subevent, RP. All of these components seem to be independently attested in the world’s languages,
line=924 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.16 bbox=72.0,373.04,538.76,383.95         :either within lexical items or across lexical items where they give rise to the kinds of paradoxes and clause
line=925 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.21 bbox=72.0,359.48,538.92,370.39         :union behavior we have found  for Hindi/Urdu. We speculate that in addition to complex predicates in this
line=926 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.24 bbox=72.0,345.92,538.61,356.83         :and other languages, productive morphological causativisation, and resultatives can be profitably analysed
line=927 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.06 bbox=72.0,332.36,538.44,343.27         :using the same framework  (see Folli and Ramchand 2002 for resultatives and goal of motion constructions
line=928 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.25 bbox=72.0,318.8,538.81,329.71          :in Italian and English; Dobnik 2002 for causative clause union constructions in Slovene; and Ramchand
line=929 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.19 bbox=72.0,305.24,538.88,316.15         :and Svenonius 2002  for an analysis of the Verb-particle construction in Germanic and Scottish Gaelic; Butt
line=930 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.24 bbox=72.0,291.8,539.04,302.71          :and Scott 2002 for an analysis of complex predicates in Chinese). The first phase syntax decomposition we
line=931 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.18 bbox=72.0,278.24,538.8,289.15          :propose and justify here makes quite specific predictions concerning the types of productive and compo-
line=932 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.19 bbox=72.0,264.68,538.66,275.59         :sitional complex predications possible in natural languages, and the way in which they will be manifested
line=933 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.19 bbox=72.0,251.12,466.18,262.03         :syntactically. We leave extensions and modifications of this framework to further research.
line=934 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.00 bbox=88.92,237.56,538.94,248.47        :    One important corollary of this approach is that the notion of the lexicon and lexical information has
line=935 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.11 bbox=72.0,224.0,538.91,234.91          :been decomposed.   We  think that this more constructionalist view of the lexicon is justified in the light of
line=936 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.11 bbox=72.0,210.44,338.67,221.35         :the complex predicate data found in this and other languages.

