line=952 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.00 bbox=93.72,557.24,539.01,568.15              :     The South Asian  languages Urdu and  Hindi are closely related. Both are among the 16 official lan-
line=953 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.16 bbox=72.0,543.68,538.92,554.59               :guages of India and are spoken primarily in the north of India. Urdu is the national language of Pakistan.
line=954 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.21 bbox=72.0,530.12,538.92,541.03               :The data presented in this paper are drawn primarily from the dialect of Urdu spoken in Lahore, Pakistan,
line=955 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.11 bbox=72.0,516.56,384.43,527.47               :as well as from examples cited in the literature on both Urdu and Hindi.
line=956 fonts=F0-10.9,F5-10.9 iscore=0.19 bbox=93.72,503.0,539.1,513.91        :     Case markers  in Urdu are clitics. The clitic ko fulfills both dative and accusative functions. The
line=957 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.25 bbox=72.0,489.44,538.74,500.35               :phonologically null case is consistently glossed as nominative. For a detailed discussion of the case system
line=958 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.12 bbox=72.0,475.88,234.39,486.79               :of Urdu see Butt and King (2000a,b).
line=959 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.00 bbox=93.72,462.32,538.72,473.23              :     Note that the ‘force do’ is actually a N-V complex predicate, but this fact does not make a difference
line=960 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.16 bbox=72.0,448.76,538.9,459.67                :for the purposes of this discussion (see Mohanan 1994 for an analysis of N-V complex predication in Hindi).
line=961 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.25 bbox=93.72,435.2,393.69,446.11               :     The infinitive also functions as a verbal noun (Butt 1993, Butt 1995).
line=962 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.14 bbox=93.72,421.76,473.68,432.67              :     Much  of the material in this section duplicates argumentation in Butt and Geuder 2001.
line=963 fonts=F0-1.6,F0-10.9 iscore=0.12 bbox=89.0,408.2,501.58,419.11         :    ZModals are ignored for the purposes of this discussion, as they function more like main verbs.
line=964 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.12 bbox=93.72,394.64,538.99,405.55              :     Mahajan  2001 points out some exceptional cases where the light verb alone does not determine the
line=965 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.18 bbox=72.0,381.08,538.84,391.99               :possibility of ergative case marking, but rather, the transitivity of the resulting form. (In the general case,
line=966 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.21 bbox=72.0,367.52,538.89,378.43               :the transitivity of the resulting V-V structure is determined by the light verb so that the two proposals are
line=967 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.11 bbox=72.0,353.96,538.62,364.87               :indistinguishable.) Mahajan’s data do not cast doubt on our claim that the light verb is crucially implicated
line=968 fonts=F0-10.9,F5-10.9 iscore=0.30 bbox=72.0,340.4,539.0,351.31         :in argument structure and case licensing, but they do highlight the fact that it is the combination of the two
line=969 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.10 bbox=72.0,326.84,538.73,337.75               :verbal pieces that is important, and that the combinations are not trivially calculable on the basis of lexical
line=970 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.24 bbox=72.0,313.28,538.89,324.19               :notations. This idea is very much in the spirit of the proposals to be made in this paper—we are attempting to
line=971 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.19 bbox=72.0,299.72,538.68,310.63               :give a precise account of the way in which verbal heads combine and the syntax that underlies the argument
line=972 fonts=F0-10.9 iscore=0.05 bbox=72.0,286.16,213.16,297.07               :structure properties that we find.
